AIDS; and the relationship between life and art. These memories she finds stored alongside memories of nature’s images of trees pulling themselves up from their roots and fleeing the forest; storms and ley lines, and skies bursting with star-like eyes. In The Queen of Peace Room, from a very personal perspective, Magie Dominic explores violence against women in the second half of the twentieth century, and in doing so unearths the memory of a generation. In eight days, she captures half a century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAdult child sexual abuse victimsvBiography. 0aAdult child sexual abuse victimsxBiography. 0aWomenxCase studiesxViolence against. 0aWomenxViolence againstvCase studies. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aHistory. 4aLife Writing. 4aReligion. 4aSocial Science: Women’s Studies. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Women.2bisacsh1 aRosenberg, Sharon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920833940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889208339423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889208339/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles